My question posted on IThome didn't get much valuable replies.
No body gave me any specific number on the cost of a website and most of them are not focusing on the topic.
Maybe I would better gather these information in EnglishI'll first gather the pricing information of the web-hosting services.
And check if I can findout what service package is subscribed by cookie caster & its litho.com.

Github and Google offer free website platforms.
I may be able to do some little experiments on those by running my website prototype on them.
This will tell me how much bandwidth and computational force are required.

After changing the imported model file format to STL,
the bug was still not fixed.
The cutte model still suffered severe glitching problem.
\The only possible cause I can imagine lies within the cutted mesh itself.
It might have proglems in its settings, or it gone wrong during the transmission between the server and the client.

There are two methods i'm going to try.
The first is to change the setting of the original mesh of ExtrudeGeometry.
The second method is  to give up forming 3D models on client side and pass the shape points directly to the server to create the extrude geometry.

If all of these methods failed, I'll consider about switching the modeling system from threejs to jscad.
Although the scale of openjscad is still small, since it clearly sets its target to CAD applications, it may sooner or later exceed three.js in this area.

